2026-04-16 12:13:42 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module switch'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show: (1) Power supply is providing correct 12 V and polarity. (2) Correct polarity appears at the control-module input. (3) At the switch, one side is at +12 V and the other side sits at ~0.36 V instead of being pulled up to 12 V when the switch is operated. (4) A later continuity test with power removed reports that the control switch itself measures as an open circuit. (5) Cabling from control output to load, and within the control module to the inverted‑cables LED and negative rail, has already been checked and found nominal. \n\nThese results are consistent with a failed (open) control-module switch: internally it no longer closes the circuit between the +12 V rail from the power supply and the outgoing positive line toward the load when actuated. The small ~0.36 V observed at the supposed output side likely comes from leakage or the previously connected measurement circuitry, not from proper conduction through the switch. Replacing/repairing the control module switch should restore continuity to the load and allow the lamp to turn on when the switch is operated.'
